[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Typically, buffer overflow protection modifies the organization of stack-allocated data so it includes a *canary* value that, when destroyed by a stack buffer overflow, shows that a buffer preceding it in memory has been overflowed.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] By verifying the canary value, execution of the affected program can be terminated, preventing it from misbehaving or from allowing an attacker to take control over it.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Other buffer overflow protection techniques include *bounds checking*, which checks accesses to each allocated block of memory so they cannot go beyond the actually allocated space, and *tagging*, which ensures that memory allocated for storing data cannot contain executable code.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Overfilling a buffer allocated on the stack is more likely to influence program execution than overfilling a buffer on the heap because the stack contains the return addresses for all active function calls.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] However, similar implementation-specific protections also exist against heap-based overflows.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] There are several implementations of buffer overflow protection, including those for the GNU Compiler Collection, LLVM, Microsoft Visual Studio, and other compilers.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] A stack buffer overflow occurs when a program writes to a memory address on the program's call stack outside of the intended data structure, which is usually a fixed-length buffer.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack buffer overflow bugs are caused when a program writes more data to a buffer located on the stack than what is actually allocated for that buffer.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] This almost always results in corruption of adjacent data on the stack, and in cases where the overflow was triggered by mistake, will often cause the program to crash or operate incorrectly.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack buffer overflow is a type of the more general programming malfunction known as buffer overflow (or buffer overrun).
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Overfilling a buffer on the stack is more likely to derail program execution than overfilling a buffer on the heap because the stack contains the return addresses for all active function calls.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack buffer overflow can be caused deliberately as part of an attack known as stack smashing.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] This is one of the oldest and more reliable methods for attackers to gain unauthorized access to a computer.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Typically, buffer overflow protection modifies the organization of data in the stack frame of a function call to include a "canary" value that, when destroyed, shows that a buffer preceding it in memory has been overflowed.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] This provides the benefit of preventing an entire class of attacks.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] According to some researchers, the performance impact of these techniques is negligible.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack-smashing protection is unable to protect against certain forms of attack.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] For example, it cannot protect against buffer overflows in the heap.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] There is no sane way to alter the layout of data within a structure; structures are expected to be the same between modules, especially with shared libraries.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Any data in a structure after a buffer is impossible to protect with canaries; thus, programmers must be very careful about how they organize their variables and use their structures.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] The terminology is a reference to the historic practice of using canaries in coal mines, since they would be affected by toxic gases earlier than the miners, thus providing a biological warning system.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Canaries are alternately known as *stack cookies*, which is meant to evoke the image of a "broken cookie" when the value is corrupted.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] There are three types of canaries in use: *terminator*, *random*, and *random XOR*.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Current versions of StackGuard support all three, while ProPolice supports *terminator* and *random* canaries.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Normally, a random canary is generated at program initialization, and stored in a global variable.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] This variable is usually padded by unmapped pages so that attempting to read it using any kinds of tricks that exploit bugs to read off RAM cause a segmentation fault, terminating the program.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] It may still be possible to read the canary if the attacker knows where it is or can get the program to read from the stack.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Random XOR canaries have the same vulnerabilities as random canaries, except that the "read from stack" method of getting the canary is a bit more complicated.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] The attacker must get the canary, the algorithm, and the control data in order to re-generate the original canary needed to spoof the protection.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] In addition, random XOR canaries can protect against a certain type of attack involving overflowing a buffer in a structure into a pointer to change the pointer to point at a piece of control data.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Because of the XOR encoding, the canary will be wrong if the control data or return value is changed.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Because of the pointer, the control data or return value can be changed without overflowing over the canary.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Although these canaries protect the control data from being altered by clobbered pointers, they do not protect any other data or the pointers themselves.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Function pointers especially are a problem here, as they can be overflowed into and can execute shellcode when called.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Bounds checking is a compiler-based technique that adds run-time bounds information for each allocated block of memory, and checks all pointers against those at run-time.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] For C and C++, bounds checking can be performed at pointer calculation time or at dereference time.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Implementations of this approach use either a central repository, which describes each allocated block of memory, or fat pointers, which contain both the pointer and additional data, describing the region that they point to.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Tagging is a compiler-based or hardware-based (requiring a tagged architecture) technique for tagging the type of a piece of data in memory, used mainly for type checking.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] By marking certain areas of memory as non-executable, it effectively prevents memory allocated to store data from containing executable code.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Also, certain areas of memory can be marked as non-allocated, preventing buffer overflows.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Historically, tagging has been used for implementing high-level programming languages; with appropriate support from the operating system, tagging can also be used to detect buffer overflows.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] An example is the NX bit hardware feature, supported by Intel, AMD and ARM processors.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack-smashing protection was first implemented by *StackGuard* in 1997, and published at the 1998 USENIX Security Symposium.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard was introduced as a set of patches to the Intel x86 backend of GCC 2.7.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard was maintained for the Immunix Linux distribution from 1998 to 2003, and was extended with implementations for terminator, random and random XOR canaries.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard was suggested for inclusion in GCC 3.x at the GCC 2003 Summit Proceedings, but this was never achieved.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] From 2001 to 2005, IBM developed GCC patches for stack-smashing protection, known as *ProPolice*.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] It improved on the idea of StackGuard by placing buffers after local pointers and function arguments in the stack frame.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] This helped avoid the corruption of pointers, preventing access to arbitrary memory locations.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Red Hat engineers identified problems with ProPolice though, and in 2005 re-implemented stack-smashing protection for inclusion in GCC 4.1.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] This work introduced the -fstack-protector flag, which protects only some vulnerable functions, and the -fstack-protector-all flag, which protects all functions whether they need it or not.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] In 2012, Google engineers implemented the -fstack-protector-strong flag to strike a better balance between security and performance.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] This flag protects more kinds of vulnerable functions than -fstack-protector does, but not every function, providing better performance than -fstack-protector-all.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] It is available in GCC since its version 4.9.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] All Fedora packages are compiled with -fstack-protector since Fedora Core 5, and -fstack-protector-strong since Fedora 20.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Most packages in Ubuntu are compiled with -fstack-protector since 6.10.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Every Arch Linux package is compiled with -fstack-protector since 2011.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] All Arch Linux packages built since 4 May 2014 use -fstack-protector-strong.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack protection is only used for some packages in Debian, and only for the FreeBSD base system since 8.0.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack protection is standard in certain operating systems, including OpenBSD, Hardened Gentoo and DragonFly BSD.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] StackGuard and ProPolice cannot protect against overflows in automatically allocated structures that overflow into function pointers.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] ProPolice at least will rearrange the allocation order to get such structures allocated before function pointers.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] A separate mechanism for pointer protection was proposed in PointGuard and is available on Microsoft Windows.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] The compiler suite from Microsoft implements buffer overflow protection since version 2003 through the /GS command-line switch, which is enabled by default since version 2005.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack-smashing protection can be turned on by the compiler flag `-qstackprotect`.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Clang supports the same -fstack-protector options as GCC and a stronger "safe stack" (-fsanitize=safe-stack) system with similarly low performance impact.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Clang also has three buffer overflow detectors, namely AddressSanitizer (`-fsanitize=address`), UBSan (`-fsanitize=bounds`), and the unofficial SafeCode (last updated for LLVM 3.0).
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] These systems have different tradeoffs in terms of performance penalty, memory overhead, and classes of detected bugs.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Stack protection is standard in certain operating systems, including OpenBSD.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Intel's C and C++ compiler supports stack-smashing protection with options similar to those provided by GCC and Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Invented by Mike Frantzen, StackGhost is a simple tweak to the register window spill–fill routines which makes buffer overflows much more difficult to exploit.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] The performance impact is negligible: less than one percent.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] The resulting gdb issues were resolved by Mark Kettenis two years later, allowing enabling of the feature.
[src:fortify-source/buffer-overflow-protection] Following this event, the StackGhost code was integrated (and optimized) into the SPARC version of the OpenBSD operating system.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The **C standard library**, sometimes referred to as **libc**, is the standard library for the C programming language, as specified in the ISO C standard.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Starting from the original ANSI C standard, it was developed at the same time as the C POSIX library, which is a superset of it.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Since ANSI C was adopted by the International Organization for Standardization, the C standard library is also called the **ISO C library**.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The C standard library provides macros, type definitions and functions for tasks such as string manipulation, mathematical computation, input/output processing, memory management, and input/output.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The application programming interface (API) of the C standard library is declared in a number of header files.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Each header file contains one or more function declarations, data type definitions, and macros.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] An implementation of a version of the standard for the C language can be described as *hosted* or *freestanding*.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] A hosted implementation supports the entire standard, and requires that all of the header files specified in the standard be present; these are typically implementations for programs running on an operating system.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] After a long period of stability, three new header files (`<iso646.h>`, `<wchar.h>`, and `<wctype.h>`) were added with *Normative Addendum 1* (NA1), an addition to the C Standard ratified in 1995.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Three of the header files (`<complex.h>`, `<stdatomic.h>`, and `<threads.h>`) are conditional features that implementations are not required to support.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The POSIX standard added several nonstandard C headers for Unix-specific functionality.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Many have found their way to other architectures.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Examples include `<fcntl.h>` and `<unistd.h>`.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] A number of other groups are using other nonstandard headers – the GNU C Library has `<alloca.h>`, and OpenVMS has the `va_count()` function.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] On Unix-like systems, the authoritative documentation of the API is provided in the form of man pages.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] On most systems, man pages on standard library functions are in section 3; section 7 may contain some more generic pages on underlying concepts (e.g.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Unix-like systems typically have a C library in shared library form, but the header files (and compiler toolchain) may be absent from an installation so C development may not be possible.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The C library is considered part of the operating system on Unix-like systems; in addition to functions specified by the C standard, it includes other functions that are part of the operating system API, such as functions specified in the POSIX standard.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The C library functions, including the ISO C standard ones, are widely used by programs, and are regarded as if they were not only an implementation of something in the C language, but also *de facto* part of the operating system interface.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Unix-like operating systems generally cannot function if the C library is erased.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] This is true for applications which are dynamically as opposed to statically linked.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Further, the kernel itself (at least in the case of Linux) operates independently of any libraries.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Compiled applications written in C are either statically linked with a C library, or linked to a dynamic version of the library that is shipped with these applications, rather than relied upon to be present on the targeted systems.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Functions in a compiler's C library are not regarded as interfaces to Microsoft Windows; the Windows system interfaces are provided in libraries separate from the C run-time library.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Many C standard library implementations exist, provided with both various operating systems and C compilers.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] However, the built-in functions must behave like ordinary functions in accordance with ISO C.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The main implication is that the program must be able to create a pointer to these functions by taking their address, and invoke the function by means of that pointer.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] If two pointers to the same function are derived in two different translation units in the program, these two pointers must compare equal; that is, the address comes by resolving the name of the function, which has external (program-wide) linkage.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Under FreeBSD and glibc, some functions such as `sin()` are not linked in by default and are instead bundled in the mathematical library libm.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] If any of them are used, the linker must be given the directive `-lm`.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] According to the C standard the macro `__STDC_HOSTED__` shall be defined to `1` if the implementation is hosted.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] A hosted implementation has all the headers specified by the C standard.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] An implementation can also be *freestanding* which means that only those headers required to be part of a freestanding implementation of the standard are guaranteed to be present.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] If an implementation is *freestanding*, it shall define `__STDC_HOSTED__` to `0`.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Some functions in the C standard library have been notorious for having buffer overflow vulnerabilities and generally encouraging buggy programming ever since their adoption.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Except the extreme case with `gets()`, all the security vulnerabilities can be avoided by introducing auxiliary code to perform memory management, bounds checking, input checking, etc.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] This is often done in the form of wrappers that make standard library functions safer and easier to use.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] This dates back to as early as *The Practice of Programming* book by B.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Pike where the authors commonly use wrappers that print error messages and quit the program if an error occurs.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The ISO C committee published Technical reports TR 24731-1 and is working on TR 24731-2 to propose adoption of some functions with bounds checking and automatic buffer allocation, correspondingly.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The former has met severe criticism with some praise, and the latter saw mixed response.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Despite concerns, TR 24731-1 was integrated into the C standards track in ISO/IEC 9899:2011 (C11), Annex K (*Bounds-checking interfaces*), and implemented approximately in Microsoft's C/++ runtime (CRT) library for the Win32 and Win64 platforms.
