[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Both Unix and C were created at AT&T's Bell Laboratories in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] During the 1970s the C language became increasingly popular.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Many universities and organizations began creating their own variants of the language for their own projects.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] By the beginning of the 1980s compatibility problems between the various C implementations became apparent.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] In 1983 the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) formed a committee to establish a standard specification of C known as "ANSI C".
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] This work culminated in the creation of the so-called C89 standard in 1989.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Part of the resulting standard was a set of software libraries called the ANSI C standard library.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Some operating systems, such as Unix-like systems, provide a system library that includes both the C standard library and other programming interfaces specific to the operating system.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] POSIX and the Single Unix Specification specify a number of routines over and above those in the basic C standard library.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The POSIX specification includes header files for, among other facilities, POSIX threads for multithreaded programm, Berkeley sockets for networking, and regular expressions.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] These are often implemented alongside the C standard library functionality, with varying degrees of closeness.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] For example, glibc implements functions such as `fork` within `libc.so`, but before the Native POSIX Thread Library was merged into glibc it constituted a separate library with its own linker flag argument.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Often, this POSIX-specified functionality will be regarded as part of the library; the basic C library may be identified as the ANSI or ISO C library.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] Some languages include the functionality of the standard C library in their own libraries.
