[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The C standard library is small compared to the standard libraries of some other languages.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The C library provides a basic set of mathematical functions, string manipulation, type conversions, and file and console-based I/O.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] It does not include a standard set of "container types/collection types" like the C++ Standard Template Library, let alone the complete graphical user interface (GUI) toolkits, networking tools, and profusion of other functionality that Java and the .NET Framework provide as standard.
[src:fortify-source/c-standard-library] The main advantage of the small standard library is that providing a working ISO C environment is much easier than it is with other languages, and consequently porting C to a new platform is comparatively easy.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In computer security, **executable-space protection** marks memory regions as non-executable, such that an attempt to execute machine code in these regions will cause an exception.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] It relies on hardware features such as the NX bit (no-execute bit), or on software emulation when hardware support is unavailable.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Software emulation often introduces a performance cost, or overhead (extra processing time or resources), while hardware-based NX bit implementations have no measurable performance impact.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The Burroughs large systems, starting with the Burroughs 5000 introduced in 1961, implemented executable-space protection using a tagged architecture.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] All accesses to code and data took place through descriptors, which had memory tags preventing them from being modified; descriptors for code did not allow the code to be modified, and descriptors for data did not allow the data to be executed as code.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Today, operating systems use executable-space protection to mark writable memory areas, such as the stack and heap, as non-executable, helping to prevent buffer overflow exploits.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] These attacks rely on some part of memory, usually the stack, being both writable and executable; if it is not, the attack fails.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Many operating systems implement or have an available executable space protection policy.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Here is a list of such systems in alphabetical order, each with technologies ordered from newest to oldest.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] A technology supplying Architecture Independent emulation will be functional on all processors which aren't hardware supported.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The "Other Supported" line is for processors which allow some grey-area method, where an explicit NX bit doesn't exist yet hardware allows one to be emulated in some way.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] As of Android 2.3 and later, architectures which support it have non-executable pages by default, including non-executable stack and heap.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Initial support for the NX bit, on x86-64 and IA-32 processors that support it, first appeared in FreeBSD -CURRENT on June 8, 2004.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] It has been in FreeBSD releases since the 5.3 release.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The Linux kernel supports the NX bit on x86-64 and IA-32 processors that support it, such as modern 64-bit processors made by AMD, Intel, Transmeta and VIA.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The support for this feature in the 64-bit mode on x86-64 CPUs was added in 2004 by Andi Kleen, and later the same year, Ingo Molnár added support for it in 32-bit mode on 64-bit CPUs.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] These features have been part of the Linux kernel mainline since the release of kernel version 2.6.8 in August 2004.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Other processors that do not support PAE are AMD K6 and earlier, Transmeta Crusoe, VIA C3 and earlier, and Geode GX and LX.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] VMware Workstation versions older than 4.0, Parallels Workstation versions older than 4.0, and Microsoft Virtual PC and Virtual Server do not support PAE on the guest.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Fedora Core 6 and Ubuntu 9.10 and later provide a kernel-PAE package which supports PAE and NX.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] NX memory protection has always been available in Ubuntu for any systems that had the hardware to support it and ran the 64-bit kernel or the 32-bit server kernel.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The 32-bit PAE desktop kernel (linux-image-generic-pae) in Ubuntu 9.10 and later, also provides the PAE mode needed for hardware with the NX CPU feature.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] For systems that lack NX hardware, the 32-bit kernels now provide an approximation of the NX CPU feature via software emulation that can help block many exploits an attacker might run from stack or heap memory.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Non-execute functionality has also been present for other non-x86 processors supporting this functionality for many releases.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Red Hat kernel developer Ingo Molnár released a Linux kernel patch named Exec Shield to approximate and utilize NX functionality on 32-bit x86 CPUs.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The Exec Shield patch was released to the Linux kernel mailing list on May 2, 2003, but was rejected for merging with the base kernel because it involved some intrusive changes to core code in order to handle the complex parts of the emulation.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Exec Shield's legacy CPU support approximates NX emulation by tracking the upper code segment limit.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] This imposes only a few cycles of overhead during context switches, which is for all intents and purposes immeasurable.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] For legacy CPUs without an NX bit, Exec Shield fails to protect pages below the code segment limit; an mprotect() call to mark higher memory, such as the stack, executable will mark all memory below that limit executable as well.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Thus, in these situations, Exec Shield's schemes fails.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] This is the cost of Exec Shield's low overhead.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Exec Shield checks for two ELF header markings, which dictate whether the stack or heap needs to be executable.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] These are called PT_GNU_STACK and PT_GNU_HEAP respectively.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Exec Shield allows these controls to be set for both binary executables and for libraries; if an executable loads a library requiring a given restriction relaxed, the executable will inherit that marking and have that restriction relaxed.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The PaX NX technology can emulate NX functionality, or use a hardware NX bit.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] PaX works on x86 CPUs that do not have the NX bit, such as 32-bit x86.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The Linux kernel still does not ship with PaX (as of May, 2007); the patch must be merged manually.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] PaX provides two methods of NX bit emulation, called SEGMEXEC and PAGEEXEC.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The SEGMEXEC method imposes a measurable but low overhead, typically less than 1%, which is a constant scalar incurred due to the virtual memory mirroring used for the separation between execution and data accesses.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] SEGMEXEC also has the effect of halving the task's virtual address space, allowing the task to access less memory than it normally could.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] This is not a problem until the task requires access to more than half the normal address space, which is rare.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] SEGMEXEC does not cause programs to use more system memory (i.e.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] RAM), it only restricts how much they can access.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] On 32-bit CPUs, this becomes 1.5 GB rather than 3 GB.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] PaX supplies a method similar to Exec Shield's approximation in the PAGEEXEC as a speedup; however, when higher memory is marked executable, this method loses its protections.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In these cases, PaX falls back to the older, variable-overhead method used by PAGEEXEC to protect pages below the CS limit, which may become quite a high-overhead operation in certain memory access patterns.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] When the PAGEEXEC method is used on a CPU supplying a hardware NX bit, the hardware NX bit is used, thus no significant overhead is incurred.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] PaX supplies mprotect() restrictions to prevent programs from marking memory in ways that produce memory useful for a potential exploit.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] This policy causes certain applications to cease to function, but it can be disabled for affected programs.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] PaX ignores both PT_GNU_STACK and PT_GNU_HEAP.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In the past, PaX had a configuration option to honor these settings but that option has been removed for security reasons, as it was deemed not useful.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The same results of PT_GNU_STACK can normally be attained by disabling mprotect() restrictions, as the program will normally mprotect() the stack on load.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] This may not always be true; for situations where this fails, simply disabling both PAGEEXEC and SEGMEXEC will effectively remove all executable space restrictions, giving the task the same protections on its executable space as a non-PaX system.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] macOS for Intel supports the NX bit on all CPUs supported by Apple (from Mac OS X 10.4.4 – the first Intel release – onwards).
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Mac OS X 10.4 only supported NX stack protection.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In Mac OS X 10.5, all 64-bit executables have NX stack and heap; W^X protection.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] This includes x86-64 (Core 2 or later) and 64-bit PowerPC on the G5 Macs.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] As of NetBSD 2.0 and later (December 9, 2004), architectures which support it have non-executable stack and heap.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Architectures that have per-page granularity consist of: alpha, amd64, hppa, i386 (with PAE), powerpc (ibm4xx), sh5, sparc (sun4m, sun4d), sparc64.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Architectures that can only support these with region granularity are: i386 (without PAE), other powerpc (such as macppc).
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Other architectures do not benefit from non-executable stack or heap; NetBSD does not by default use any software emulation to offer these features on those architectures.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] A technology in the OpenBSD operating system, known as W^X, marks writable pages by default as non-executable on processors that support that.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] On 32-bit x86 processors, the code segment is set to include only part of the address space, to provide some level of executable space protection.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] OpenBSD 3.3 shipped May 1, 2003, and was the first to include W^X.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Solaris has supported globally disabling stack execution on SPARC processors since Solaris 2.6 (1997); in Solaris 9 (2002), support for disabling stack execution on a per-executable basis was added.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The first implementation of a non-executable stack for Windows (NT 4.0, 2000 and XP) was published by SecureWave via their SecureStack product in 2001, based on the work of PaX.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Starting with Windows XP Service Pack 2 (2004) and Windows Server 2003 Service Pack 1 (2005), the NX features were implemented for the first time on the x86 architecture.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Executable space protection on Windows is called "Data Execution Prevention" (DEP).
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Under Windows XP or Server 2003 NX protection was used on critical Windows services exclusively by default.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] If the x86 processor supported this feature in hardware, then the NX features were turned on automatically in Windows XP/Server 2003 by default.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] If the feature was not supported by the x86 processor, then no protection was given.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Early implementations of DEP provided no address space layout randomization (ASLR), which allowed potential return-to-libc attacks that could have been feasibly used to disable DEP during an attack.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The PaX documentation elaborates on why ASLR is necessary; a proof-of-concept was produced detailing a method by which DEP could be circumvented in the absence of ASLR.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] It may be possible to develop a successful attack if the address of prepared data such as corrupted images or MP3s can be known by the attacker.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Microsoft added ASLR functionality in Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] On this platform, DEP is implemented through the automatic use of PAE kernel in 32-bit Windows and the native support on 64-bit kernels.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Windows Vista DEP works by marking certain parts of memory as being intended to hold only data, which the NX or XD bit enabled processor then understands as non-executable.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In Windows, from version Vista, whether DEP is enabled or disabled for a particular process can be viewed on the *Processes/Details* tab in the Windows Task Manager.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Windows implements software DEP (without the use of the NX bit) through Microsoft's "Safe Structured Exception Handling" (SafeSEH).
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] For properly compiled applications, SafeSEH checks that, when an exception is raised during program execution, the exception's handler is one defined by the application as it was originally compiled.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The effect of this protection is that an attacker is not able to add his own exception handler which he has stored in a data page through unchecked program input.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] When NX is supported, it is enabled by default.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Windows allows programs to control which pages disallow execution through its API as well as through the section headers in a PE file.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In the API, runtime access to the NX bit is exposed through the Win32 API calls VirtualAlloc[Ex] and VirtualProtect[Ex].
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Each page may be individually flagged as executable or non-executable.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Despite the lack of previous x86 hardware support, both executable and non-executable page settings have been provided since the beginning.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] On pre-NX CPUs, the presence of the 'executable' attribute has no effect.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] It was documented as if it did function, and, as a result, most programmers used it properly.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In the PE file format, each section can specify its executability.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] The execution flag has existed since the beginning of the format and standard linkers have always used this flag correctly, even long before the NX bit.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Because of this, Windows is able to enforce the NX bit on old programs.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Assuming the programmer complied with "best practices", applications should work correctly now that NX is actually enforced.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Only in a few cases have there been problems; Microsoft's own .NET Runtime had problems with the NX bit and was updated.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] In Microsoft's Xbox, although the CPU does not have the NX bit, newer versions of the XDK set the code segment limit to the beginning of the kernel's **.data** section (no code should be after this point in normal circumstances).
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Starting with version 51xx, this change was also implemented into the kernel of new Xboxes.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] This broke the techniques old exploits used to become a terminate-and-stay-resident program.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] However, new exploits were quickly released supporting this new kernel version because the fundamental vulnerability in the Xbox kernel was unaffected.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Where code is written and executed at runtime—a JIT compiler is a prominent example—the compiler can potentially be used to produce exploit code (e.g. using JIT Spray) that has been flagged for execution and therefore would not be trapped.
[src:fortify-source/executable-space-protection] Return-oriented programming can allow an attacker to execute arbitrary code even when executable space protection is enforced.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] The **GNU C Library**, commonly known as **glibc**, is the GNU Project implementation of the C standard library.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] It provides a wrapper around the system calls of the Linux kernel and other kernels for application use.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Despite its name, it now also directly supports C++ (and, indirectly, other programming languages).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] It was started in the 1980s by the Free Software Foundation (FSF) for the GNU operating system.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] glibc is free software released under the GNU Lesser General Public License.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] The GNU C Library project provides the core libraries for the GNU system, as well as many systems that use Linux as the kernel.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] These libraries provide critical APIs including ISO C11, POSIX.1-2008, BSD, OS-specific APIs and more.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] These APIs include such foundational facilities as open, read, write, malloc, printf, getaddrinfo, dlopen, pthread_create, crypt, login, exit and more.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] The glibc project was initially written mostly by Roland McGrath, working for the Free Software Foundation (FSF) in the summer of 1987 as a teenager.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In February 1988, FSF described glibc as having nearly completed the functionality required by ANSI C.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] By 1992, it had the ANSI C-1989 and POSIX.1-1990 functions implemented and work was under way on POSIX.2.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In September 1995 Ulrich Drepper made his first contribution to the glibc and by 1997 most commits were made by him.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Drepper held the maintainership position for many years and until 2012 accumulated 63% of all commits to the project.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In May 2009, glibc was migrated to a Git repository.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In 2010, a licensing issue was resolved which was caused by the Sun RPC implementation in glibc that was not GPL compatible.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] It was fixed by re-licensing the Sun RPC components under the BSD license.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In 2014, glibc suffered from an ABI breakage bug on s390.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In July 2017, 30 years after he started glibc, Roland McGrath announced his departure, "declaring myself maintainer emeritus and withdrawing from direct involvement in the project.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] These past several months, if not the last few years, have proven that you don't need me anymore".
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In 2018, maintainer Raymond Nicholson removed a joke about abortion from the glibc source code.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] It was restored later by Alexandre Oliva after Richard Stallman demanded to have it returned.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In 2021, the copyright assignment requirement to the Free Software Foundation was removed from the project.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In 1994, the developers of the Linux kernel forked glibc.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Their fork, "Linux libc", was maintained separately until around 1998.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Because the copyright attribution was insufficient, changes could not be merged back to the GNU Libc.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] The last-used version of Linux libc used the internal name (soname) libc.so.5.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In 2009, Debian and a number of derivatives switched from glibc to the variant eglibc.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Eglibc was supported by a consortium consisting of Freescale, MIPS, MontaVista and Wind River.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] It contained changes that made it more suitable for embedded usage and had added support for architectures that were not supported by glibc, such as the PowerPC e500.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] The code of eglibc was merged back into glibc at version 2.20.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] The Yocto Project and Debian also moved back to glibc since the release of Debian Jessie.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Starting in 2001 the library's development had been overseen by a committee, with Ulrich Drepper kept as the lead contributor and maintainer.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] The steering committee installation was surrounded by a public controversy, as it was openly described by Ulrich Drepper as a failed hostile takeover maneuver by Richard Stallman.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] In addition, glibc also provides extensions that have been deemed useful or necessary while developing GNU.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] glibc is used in systems that run many different kernels and different hardware architectures.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Its most common use is in systems using the Linux kernel on x86 hardware, however, officially supported hardware includes: ARM, ARC, C-SKY, DEC Alpha, IA-64, Motorola m68k, MicroBlaze, MIPS, Nios II, PA-RISC, PowerPC, RISC-V, s390, SPARC, and x86 (old versions support TILE).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] It officially supports the Hurd and Linux kernels.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Additionally, there are heavily patched versions that run on the kernels of FreeBSD and NetBSD (from which Debian GNU/kFreeBSD and Debian GNU/NetBSD systems are built, respectively), as well as a forked-version of OpenSolaris.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] It is also used (in an edited form) and named libroot.so in BeOS and Haiku.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] glibc has been criticized as being "bloated" and slower than other libraries in the past, e.g. by Linus Torvalds and embedded Linux programmers.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] For this reason, several alternative C standard libraries have been created which emphasize a smaller footprint.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] However, many small-device projects use GNU libc over the smaller alternatives because of its application support, standards compliance, and completeness.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] Examples include Openmoko and Familiar Linux for iPaq handhelds (when using the GPE display software).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] There are compatibility layers ("shims") to allow programs written for other ecosystems to run on glibc interface offering systems.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-c-library] These include libhybris, a compatibility layer for Android's Bionic, and Wine, which can be seen as a compatibility layer from Windows APIs to glibc and other native APIs available on Unix-like systems.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The **GNU Compiler Collection** (**GCC**; formerly **GNU C Compiler**) is a collection of compilers from the GNU Project that support various programming languages, hardware architectures, and operating systems.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The Free Software Foundation (FSF) distributes GCC as free software under the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC is a key component of the GNU toolchain which is used for most projects related to GNU and the Linux kernel.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] With roughly 15 million lines of code in 2019, GCC is one of the largest free programs in existence.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] It has played an important role in the growth of free software, as both a tool and an example.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] When it was first released in 1987 by Richard Stallman, GCC 1.0 was named the *GNU C Compiler* since it only handled the C programming language.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] It was extended to compile C++ in December of that year.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Front ends were later developed for Objective-C, Objective-C++, Fortran, Ada, Go, D, Modula-2, Rust, COBOL, and ALGOL 68 among others.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The OpenMP and OpenACC specifications are also supported in the C and C++ compilers.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] As well as being the official compiler of the GNU operating system, GCC has been adopted as the standard compiler by many other modern Unix-like computer operating systems, including most Linux distributions.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Most BSD family operating systems also switched to GCC shortly after its release, although since then, FreeBSD and Apple macOS have moved to the Clang compiler, largely due to licensing reasons.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC can also compile code for Windows, Android, iOS, Solaris, HP-UX, AIX, and MS-DOS compatible operating systems.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC has been ported to more platforms and instruction set architectures than any other compiler, and is widely deployed as a tool in the development of both free and proprietary software.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC is also available for many embedded systems, including ARM-based and Power ISA-based chips.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In late 1983, in an effort to bootstrap the GNU operating system, Richard Stallman asked Andrew S.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Tanenbaum, the author of the Amsterdam Compiler Kit (also known as the *Free University* *Compiler Kit*), for permission to use that software for GNU.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] When Tanenbaum advised him that the compiler itself was not free, but rather only the university, Stallman decided to work on a different compiler.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] His initial plan was to rewrite an existing compiler from Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory for the Pastel language, written in Pastel, with some help from Len Tower and others.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Stallman wrote a new C front end for the Livermore compiler, but then realized that it required megabytes of stack space, an impossibility on a 68000 Unix system that didn't allow more than 64 KB of stack space, and concluded he would have to write a new compiler from scratch.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] None of the Pastel compiler code ended up in GCC, though Stallman did use the C front end he had written in Pastel.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC was first released March 22, 1987, available by FTP from MIT.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Stallman was listed as the author but cited others for their contributions, including Tower for "parts of the parser, RTL generator, RTL definitions, and of the Vax machine description", Jack Davidson and Christopher W.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Fraser for the idea of using RTL as an intermediate language, and Paul Rubin for writing most of the preprocessor.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Described as the "first free software hit" by Peter H.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Salus, the GNU compiler arrived just at the time when Sun Microsystems was unbundling its development tools from its operating system, selling them separately at a higher combined price than the previous bundle, which led many of Sun's users to buy or download GCC instead of the vendor's tools.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] While Stallman considered GNU Emacs as his main project, by 1990 GCC supported thirteen computer architectures, was outperforming several vendor compilers, and was used commercially by several companies.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] As GCC was licensed under the GPL, programmers wanting to work in other directions—particularly those writing interfaces for languages other than C—were free to develop their own fork of the compiler, provided they meet the GPL's terms, including its requirements to distribute source code.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Multiple forks proved inefficient and unwieldy, however, and the difficulty in getting work accepted by the official GCC project was greatly frustrating for many, as the project favored stability over new features.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The FSF kept such close control on what was added to the official version of GCC 2.x (developed since 1992) that GCC was used as one example of the "cathedral" development model in Eric S.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Raymond's essay *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In 1997, a group of developers formed the *Experimental/Enhanced GNU Compiler System (EGCS)* to merge several experimental forks into a single project.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The basis of the merger was a development snapshot of GCC (taken around the 2.7.2 and later followed up to 2.8.1 release).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Mergers included g77 (Fortran), PGCC (P5 Pentium-optimized GCC), many C++ improvements, and many new architectures and operating system variants.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] With the release of GCC 2.95 in July 1999 the two projects were once again united.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC has since been maintained by a varied group of programmers from around the world under the direction of a steering committee.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC 3 (2002) removed a front-end for CHILL due to a lack of maintenance.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Before version 4.0 the Fortran front end was `g77`, which only supported FORTRAN 77, but later was dropped in favor of the new GNU Fortran front end that supports Fortran 95 and large parts of Fortran 2003 and Fortran 2008 as well.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] As of version 4.8, GCC is implemented in C++.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Support for Cilk Plus existed from GCC 5 to GCC 7.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC has been ported to a wide variety of instruction set architectures, and is widely deployed as a tool in the development of both free and proprietary software.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC is also available for many embedded systems, including Symbian (called *gcce*), ARM-based, and Power ISA-based chips.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The compiler can target a wide variety of platforms, including video game consoles such as the PlayStation 2, Cell SPE of PlayStation 3, and Dreamcast.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] It has been ported to "more than 60 platforms".
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Versions prior to GCC 7 also supported Java (`gcj`), allowing compilation of Java to native machine code.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Third-party front ends exist for many languages, such as Pascal (`gpc`), Mercury, Modula-3, VHDL (`GHDL`) and PL/I.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] A few experimental branches exist to support additional languages, such as the GCC UPC compiler for Unified Parallel C.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The default target for C++ since GCC 15.1 is *gnu++20*, a superset of C++20, and the default target for C since GCC 15 is *gnu23*, a superset of C23, with strict standard support also available.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC also provides experimental support for C2Y, C++23, and C++26.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC's external interface follows Unix conventions.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Users invoke a language-specific driver program (`gcc` for C, `g++` for C++, etc.), which interprets command arguments, calls the actual compiler, runs the assembler on the output, and then optionally runs the linker to produce a complete executable binary.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Each of the language compilers is a separate program that reads source code and outputs machine code.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] A per-language front end parses the source code in that language and produces an abstract syntax tree ("tree" for short).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] These are, if necessary, converted to the middle end's input representation, called *GENERIC* form; the middle end then gradually transforms the program towards its final form.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Compiler optimizations and static code analysis techniques (such as FORTIFY_SOURCE, a compiler directive that attempts to discover some buffer overflows) are applied to the code.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] These work on multiple representations, mostly the architecture-independent GIMPLE representation and the architecture-dependent RTL representation.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Finally, machine code is produced using architecture-specific pattern matching originally based on an algorithm of Jack Davidson and Chris Fraser.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC was written primarily in C except for parts of the Ada front end.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The distribution includes the standard libraries for Ada and C++ whose code is mostly written in those languages.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] On some platforms, the distribution also includes a low-level runtime library, **libgcc**, written in a combination of machine-independent C and processor-specific machine code, designed primarily to handle arithmetic operations that the target processor cannot perform directly.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC uses many additional tools in its build, many of which are installed by default by many Unix and Linux distributions (but which, normally, aren't present in Windows installations), including Perl, Flex, Bison, and other common tools.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In addition, it currently requires three additional libraries to be present in order to build: GMP, MPC, and MPFR.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In May 2010, the GCC steering committee decided to allow use of a C++ compiler to compile GCC.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The compiler was intended to be written mostly in C plus a subset of features from C++.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In particular, this was decided so that GCC's developers could use the destructors and generics features of C++.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In August 2012, the GCC steering committee announced that GCC now uses C++ as its implementation language.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] This means that to build GCC from sources, a C++ compiler is required that understands ISO/IEC C++03 standard.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] On May 18, 2020, GCC moved away from ISO/IEC C++03 standard to ISO/IEC C++11 standard (i.e. needed to compile, bootstrap, the compiler itself; by default it however compiles later versions of C++).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Each front end uses a parser to produce the abstract syntax tree of a given source file.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Due to the syntax tree abstraction, source files of any of the different supported languages can be processed by the same back end.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC started out using LALR parsers generated with Bison, but gradually switched to hand-written recursive-descent parsers for C++ in 2004, and for C and Objective-C in 2006.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] As of 2021 all front ends use hand-written recursive-descent parsers.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Until GCC 4.0, the tree representation of the program was not fully independent of the processor being targeted.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The meaning of a tree was somewhat different for different language front ends, and front ends could provide their own tree codes.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] This was simplified with the introduction of GENERIC and GIMPLE, two new forms of language-independent trees that were introduced with the advent of GCC 4.0.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GENERIC is more complex, based on the GCC 3.x Java front end's intermediate representation.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GIMPLE is a simplified GENERIC, in which various constructs are *lowered* to multiple GIMPLE instructions.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The C, C++, and Java front ends produce GENERIC directly in the front end.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Other front ends instead have different intermediate representations after parsing and convert these to GENERIC.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In either case, the so-called "gimplifier" then converts this more complex form into the simpler SSA-based GIMPLE form that is the common language for a large number of language- and architecture-independent global (function scope) optimizations.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The middle stage of GCC does all of the code analysis and optimization, working independently of both the compiled language and the target architecture, starting from the GENERIC representation and expanding it to register transfer language (RTL).
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The GENERIC representation contains only the subset of the imperative programming constructs optimized by the middle end.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] In transforming the source code to GIMPLE, complex expressions are split into a three-address code using temporary variables.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] This representation was inspired by the SIMPLE representation proposed in the McCAT compiler by Laurie J.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Hendren for simplifying the analysis and optimization of imperative programs.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The exact set of GCC optimizations varies from release to release as it develops, but includes the standard algorithms, such as loop optimization, jump threading, common subexpression elimination, instruction scheduling, and so forth.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The RTL optimizations are of less importance with the addition of global SSA-based optimizations on GIMPLE trees, as RTL optimizations have a much more limited scope, and have less high-level information.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Some of these optimizations performed at this level include dead-code elimination, partial-redundancy elimination, global value numbering, sparse conditional constant propagation, and scalar replacement of aggregates.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Array dependence based optimizations such as automatic vectorization and automatic parallelization are also performed.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Profile-guided optimization is also possible.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The GCC project includes an implementation of the C++ Standard Library called libstdc++, licensed under the GPLv3 License with an exception to link non-GPL-compatible applications when sources are built with GCC.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Since GCC Version 3, the C++ ABI is based on the ABI published by Intel for the Itanium C++ ABI.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] optimizes across object file boundaries to directly improve the linked binary.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] representation included in the object file.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The file is generated alongside the object file during source compilation.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Each source compilation generates a separate object file and link-time helper file.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] When the object files are linked, the compiler is executed again and uses the helper files to optimize code across the separately compiled object files.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Plugins allow a stock compiler to be tailored to specific needs by external code loaded as plugins.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The support of plugins was once a contentious issue in 2007.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The C++ language has an active proposal for transactional memory.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] , the feature has only been supported since GCC 10.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The feature is optional in C, but has been made available too since this change.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The primary supported (and best tested) processor families are 64- and 32-bit ARM, 64- and 32-bit x86 64 and x86 and 64-bit PowerPC and SPARC.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The GCJ Java compiler can target either a native machine language architecture or the Java virtual machine's Java bytecode.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] When retargeting GCC to a new platform, bootstrapping is often used.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] Motorola 68000, Zilog Z80, and other processors are also targeted in the GCC versions developed for various Texas Instruments, Hewlett Packard, Sharp, and Casio programmable graphing calculators.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] GCC is licensed under the GNU General Public License version 3.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] The *GCC runtime exception* permits compilation of proprietary programs (in addition to free software) with GCC headers and runtime libraries.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] This does not impact the license terms of GCC source code.
[src:fortify-source/gnu-compiler-collection] For example, when non-GPL-compatible software is used together with GCC within the Compile Process, following the GPLv3 for all of the propagated object code GCC generates, becomes mandatory as it is derived from the GPL-licensed libraries.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] In computer security, **hardening** or **system hardening** is usually the process of securing a system by making it a 'hard target' by reducing its attack surface vulnerabilities.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] The attack surface is larger when a system performs more functions; in principle a single-function system is more secure than a multipurpose one.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] Hardening is considered an important component of cybersecurity.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] Reducing available ways of attack typically includes changing default passwords, the removal of unnecessary software, unnecessary usernames or logins, and the disabling or removal of unnecessary services.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] It may also involve patching vulnerabilities and switching off ancillary services that are not essential.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] Hardening measures can also include setting up intrusion prevention systems, disabling or restricting accounts, reducing file system permissions, using encrypted network connections and enabling host-based network security.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] Binary hardening is a security technique in which binary executables are analyzed and modified to protect against common exploits.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] Binary hardening is independent of compilers and involves the entire toolchain.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] For example, one binary hardening technique is to detect potential buffer overflows and to substitute the existing code with safer code.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] The advantage of manipulating binaries is that vulnerabilities in legacy code can be fixed automatically without the need for source code, which may be unavailable or obfuscated.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] Secondly, the same techniques can be applied to binaries from multiple compilers, some of which may be less secure than others.
[src:fortify-source/hardening-computing] Binary hardening often involves the non-deterministic modification of control flow and instruction addresses so as to prevent attackers from successfully reusing program code to perform exploits.
